<h1>@HI{{noni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vplain{{}}(nonpast, volitional) @HI{{<strong>noni</strong>}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

The main clause following <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong> expresses something necessary for the preceding clause to come about.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono @KT{{repo-to}}wo @KJ{{write}}ku <strong>noni</strong> @KJ{{one}}ka@KJ{{month}}kakarimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    It took me a month to write this paper.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

With <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong> only nonpast volitional verbs in the plain form may be used.
<p></p>

When the verb is one of motion and no location is specified <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong> cannot be used. In this case use V@HI{{masu ni}} instead.
<p></p>

